{"meta":{"spec_version":"0.3","created":"2025-01-01T00:00:00Z","author":"OpenChronology Demo"},"event":{"id":"viking-age","type":"era","content":{"title":"The Viking Age","date_label":"793 CE – 1066 CE","description":"The **Viking Age** began with the raid on Lindisfarne monastery in 793 CE and ended with the Norman Conquest of England in 1066. During this period, Norse seafarers from Scandinavia explored, traded, raided, and settled across an enormous arc — from Newfoundland in the west to the Caspian Sea in the east.\n\nVikings founded Dublin, established the Kievan Rus, colonized Iceland and Greenland, and reached North America five centuries before Columbus. Far from the one-dimensional raiders of popular imagination, they were skilled merchants, craftspeople, and colonizers who profoundly shaped the political map of medieval Europe.\n\nThe age ended not with a single event but with the gradual Christianization and integration of Scandinavian kingdoms into the broader European political order.","description_format":"markdown","tags":["vikings","norse","scandinavia","exploration","raid"],"sources":[{"title":"Viking Age — Encyclopedia Britannica","url":"https://www.britannica.com/topic/Viking-Age"}]},"temporal":{"calendar":"gregorian","start_value":"793","end_value":"1066","precision":"year"},"significance":{"value":820,"temporal_scope":"centuries","geographic_scope":"northern-europe"}}}
